oad either through the `--hotreload` flag with `dotnet test`, the `TESTINGPLATFORM_HOTRELOAD_ENABLED=1` environment variable, or by setting `<TestingPlatformHotReload>true</TestingPlatformHotReload>` in the .csproj PropertyGroup. The MSBuild property approach seems like the cleanest way to make it always enabled without needing environment variables or command-line flags each time. The Microsoft Testing Platform supports hot reload through the CLI flag, an environment variable, or an MSBuild property. Since the user wants this always enabled at the project level, I'll add the MSBuild property to the .csproj file.","outputTokens":1351,"requestId":"A02F:252559:19B42AD:1D29E2E:69FE90EF"},"id":"6dc9a9a6-74b5-4ac8-8592-de65c0e41783","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:42:31.714Z","parentId":"4b213329-15fa-46e0-9368-c458dbe2bb1f"}
